from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline 
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from pylab import *

breast_cancer = datasets.load_breast_cancer()

X = breast_cancer.data
y = breast_cancer.target
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, stratify=y, random_state=40)

begin = 1
end = 300
step = 4

auc_list = [[],[]]

for k in range(begin, end+1):
    neigh = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn_model = Pipeline([
                        ("scaler", scaler),
                        ("knn", neigh)
                        ])
    knn_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # predict probabilities
    y_pred = knn_model.predict_proba(X_test) 

    # keep probabilities for the positive outcome only
    y_pred = y_pred[:, 1]

    if k%step == 1 and k <20:
        fpr, tpr, tresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
        plt.plot(fpr,tpr,label='k%i'%k)
    # calculate scores
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
    auc_list[0].append(k)
    auc_list[1].append(auc)

    

# axis labels
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
# show the title
plt.title('ROC values for different values of k')
# show the plot
plt.legend()
plt.show()



plt.plot(auc_list[0], auc_list[1])
plt.title('AUC values per k value')
plt.xlabel('k value')
plt.ylabel('AUC value')
plt.show()

It can be observed that for this model, k-values between approximately 3 and 20 the area under the ROC curve seem to be performing appropriately, as the areas under their corresponding ROC curves are the highest. It can be seen that this area declines slowly for increasing k after 20.
